{"title_page": "Alfred National Park", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Alfred Park]], a park in [[India]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                   = protected\n| name                   = Alfred National Park\n| state                  = vic\n| iucn_category          = II\n| image                  = Ferns near cann river panorama.jpg\n| caption                = Ferns within the Alfred National Park\n| image_alt              = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|37|34|17|S|149|21|37|E|display=inline,title}}\n| force_national_map     = \n| relief                 = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| map_alt                = \n| nearest_town_or_city   = [[Cann River, Victoria|Cann River]]\n| area                   = 30.50\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=vg/>\n| established            = 1925\n| established_footnotes  = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/alfred-national-park|title=Alfred National Park|work=Parks Victoria|date=|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n| visitation_num         = \n| visitation_year        = \n| visitation_footnotes   = \n| managing_authorities   = Parks Victoria\n| url                    = http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/alfred-national-park\n}}\nThe '''Alfred National Park''' is a [[national park]] located in the [[East Gippsland]] region of the [[Australia]]n [[States and territories of Australia|state]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. The {{convert|3050|ha|acre|adj=on}}<ref name=vg>{{cite book|title=Alfred National Park Visitor Guide|date=April 2008|publisher=Parks Victoria|pages=2 |url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/313156/Park-note-Alfred-National-Park.pdf }}</ref> national park is situated approximately {{convert|388|km}} east of [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]] and was declared in 1925.\n\nThe park is dissected by the [[Princes Highway#Victoria|Princes Highway]], between {{VICcity|Cann River}} and {{VICcity|Genoa}}.\n\n==Features==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2014}}\nThe park reserves examples of warm temperate [[rainforest]], particularly the jungle of [[Mount Drummer, Victoria|Mount Drummer]]. Compared to the tropical rainforests of [[Queensland]] and [[New South Wales]], this is a floristically [[depauperate]] forest, representing as it does the southern limit of this flora. This region is biogeographically interesting as the meeting point between the [[subtropical]] flora of the north of Australia and the cool [[temperate]] and [[arid]] zone floras of the south and west. The rainforest community consists of a closed canopy of Lilly Pilly ''[[Acmena smithii]]'' with numerous [[liana]]s, [[fern]]s and [[epiphyte]]s. The park is particularly known for occurrence of four varieties of tree ferns and of epiphytic [[orchid]]s such as the orange-blossom orchid ''[[Sarcochilus falcatus]]'' and the rock orchid ''[[Dendrobium speciosum]]''. The park was burnt quite badly in the 1983 '[[Ash Wednesday]]' bushfires.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Australia|environment}}}}\n* [[Protected areas of Victoria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/313335/Lind-and-Alfred-National-Parks.pdf|type=PDF|title=Lind and Alfred National Parks Management Plan|date=August 1998|work=Parks Victoria|publisher=Government of Victoria|isbn=0-7306-6265-9 }}\n\n{{National Parks of Victoria}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:East Gippsland]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Alfred Park]], a park in [[India]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                   = protected\n| name                   = Alfred National Park\n| state                  = vic\n| iucn_category          = II\n| image                  = Ferns near cann river panorama.jpg\n| caption                = Ferns within the Alfred National Park\n| image_alt              = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|37|34|17|S|149|21|37|E|display=inline,title}}\n| force_national_map     = \n| relief                 = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| map_alt                = \n| nearest_town_or_city   = [[Cann River, Victoria|Cann River]]\n| area                   = 30.50\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=vg/>\n| established            = 1925\n| established_footnotes  = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/alfred-national-park|title=Alfred National Park|work=Parks Victoria|date=|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n| visitation_num         = \n| visitation_year        = \n| visitation_footnotes   = \n| managing_authorities   = Parks Victoria\n| url                    = http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/explore/parks/alfred-national-park\n}}\nThe '''Alfred National Park''' is a [[national park]] located in the [[East Gippsland]] region of the [[Australia]]n [[States and territories of Australia|state]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. The {{convert|3050|ha|acre|adj=on}}<ref name=vg>{{cite book|title=Alfred National Park Visitor Guide|date=April 2008|publisher=Parks Victoria|pages=2 |url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/313156/Park-note-Alfred-National-Park.pdf }}</ref> national park is situated approximately {{convert|388|km}} east of [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]] and was declared in 1925.\n\nThe park is dissected by the [[Princes Highway#Victoria|Princes Highway]], between {{VICcity|Cann River}} and {{VICcity|Genoa}}.\n\n==Features==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2014}}\nThe park reserves examples of warm temperate [[rainforest]], particularly the jungle of [[Mount Drummer, Victoria|Mount Drummer]]. Compared to the tropical rainforests of [[Queensland]] and [[New South Wales]], this is a floristically [[depauperate]] forest, representing as it does the southern limit of this flora. This region is biogeographically interesting as the meeting point between the [[subtropical]] flora of the north of Australia and the cool [[temperate]] and [[arid]] zone floras of the south and west. The rainforest community consists of a closed canopy of Lilly Pilly ''[[Acmena smithii]]'' with numerous [[liana]]s, [[fern]]s and [[epiphyte]]s. The park is particularly known for occurrence of four varieties of tree ferns and of epiphytic [[orchid]]s such as the orange-blossom orchid ''[[Sarcochilus falcatus]]'' and the rock orchid ''[[Dendrobium speciosum]]''. The park was burnt quite badly in the 1983 '[[Ash Wednesday]]' bushfires.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Australia|environment}}}}\n* [[Protected areas of Victoria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://parkweb.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/313335/Lind-and-Alfred-National-Parks.pdf|type=PDF|title=Lind and Alfred National Parks Management Plan|date=August 1998|work=Parks Victoria|publisher=Government of Victoria|isbn=0-7306-6265-9 }}\n\n{{National Parks of Victoria}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:East Gippsland]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "Rosey Chan", "text_new": "'''Rosey Chan''' is a multimedia artist. \n\nA virtuoso musician who studied piano and composition at the Royal College of Music, Rosey\u2019s creative output spans a wide range. \n\nHer solo concerts incorporate cinematic visuals and combine her own compositions with selected classical repertoire and electronic fusion. \n\nHer interests in collaborative projects have taken her into a world of contrasted disciplines; Architecture, Design, Poetic Spoken word, Contemporary dance, Experimental music, and Film composition. \n\nRosey is a [[Steinway Artist]].\n\n\n==Background==\n\nRosey Chan was born in the [[United Kingdom]] to Chinese parents. She attended the [[Royal Academy of Music]] on a piano scholarship. She then went on to be classically trained in composition, piano and violin at the [[Royal College of Music]] in [[South Kensington]], London. She also plays guitar, accordion, and keyboards.\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter graduating from the Royal College of Music, Chan performed in a contemporary female duo (two pianos) which performed at such venues as the [[Royal Albert Hall]], [[Wigmore Hall]], [[Royal Festival Hall]] and [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/jul/15/classicalmusicandopera Yukawa/Chan, Wigmore Hall, London | Music | The Guardian<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3634861/Charm-and-thrills.html Charm and thrills - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Chan focused on her solo career and expanded her repertoire to include contemporary electronic music, improvisation,<ref>[http://jazzwisemagazine.com/component/content/article/67-daily-breaking-news/2010/11592-jazz-breaking-news-mike-figgis-begins-kings-place-residency-?Itemid=101 Jazzwise magazine<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.remotegoat.com/uk/review_view.php?uid=4109 Rosey Chan Review 5 stars (UK)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> film scoring, performance art and working with dance. She has presented her work at [[The Royal Opera House]], The Royal Festival Hall, [[Pompidou Centre]] to the intimate settings of [[100 Club|The 100 club]], [[(Le) Poisson Rouge|Le Poisson Rouge]] in New York, [[Gagosian Gallery]] Paris and [[Serpentine Galleries|The Serpentine Gallery]] London.\n\nContemporary art installations are an extension of Rosey Chan's work. Her multi-media performance piece ''March of the Jingoists'' premiered at the 2009 [[Frieze Art Fair]].<ref>[http://www.wallpaper.com/art/frieze-week-report/3861 Frieze week report | Art | Wallpaper* Magazine<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Her three-screen video installation ''Past Present Future'' premiered at the 2010 Hong Kong Art Fair.\n\nArtists she has worked with include: [[Marina Abramovic]], [[Doug Aitken]], [[Fanny Ardant]], [[Antony Gormley]], [[Patrik Schumacher]], [[Zaha Hadid Architects]], [[Charles Dance]], [[Jonas Mekas]], [https://www.businessoffashion.com/community/people/zowie-broach Zowie Broach], [[Nick Knight (photographer)|Nick Knight]], Central School of Ballet and Dance.\n\nMusicians she has collaborated with include: [[William Orbit]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], Synematik, Stargate Music, [[Michael Nyman]], Carnet de Voyage Music, [[The Invisible Men]], [[Ali Tennant]], [[Ilan Eshkeri]], [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1921196/ Gregg Wilson], [[Mike Figgis]], Vaal, [[Victoria Bond]], [[English Chamber Orchestra|The English Chamber Orchestra]], [[London Contemporary Orchestra]].\n\nIn 2009, Chan co-founded a piece of music, food and wine festival in Tuscany with Luca Sanjust, [[Mike Figgis]] and ex-''[[Wine Spectator]]'' editor [[James Suckling]].\n\nIn 2011 Chan curated cultural content for the first Hong Kong Liberatum Festival, an international cultural festival, and summit, bringing together diverse talents from Europe, America, and China. The project culminated in workshops for students in music, film, architecture, and photography, alongside talks and performances throughout the festival.<ref>[http://www.liberatum.org.uk/rosey-chan-has-been-appointed-creative-director-of-the-first-hong-kong-liberatum-festival/ Rosey Chan has been appointed Creative Director of the first Hong Kong Liberatum Festival | Liberatum - Connecting the world's finest artistic minds<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nChan supports environmental charity [[Client Earth]]. She composed and recorded an ''Adagio for Planet Earth'' which she has dedicated to the charity.\n\n===Solo releases===\n\nChan released her debut album ''ONE'' in 2010. It was produced by the singer-songwriter [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]<ref name=\"kb\">[https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/8-years-of-my-life/1360143240]{{Citation|title=8 Years Of My Life|date=2010-03-10|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/8-years-of-my-life/1360143240|language=en-GB|accessdate=2018-04-01}}</ref> and featured tracks by, [[Bach]], [[Debussy]], [[Bill Evans]] and [[Tom Waits]].\nHer second album ''[https://open.spotify.com/album/0tPclGhClSnrysCtQI0AD0 8 years of my life]'' was released in March 2018 with a limited edition vinyl of her solo piano improvisations. She released an electronic album in 2019 under the band name [https://open.spotify.com/artist/7n0My4uAsbPhrImLTD0QUF Carnet de Voyage Music]\n\n==Today==\n\nChan currently lives in London. She performs and collaborates on various dance, visual art, architecture, film, fashion, music and design projects internationally.<ref>[http://www.vogue.it/en/people-are-talking-about/from-london/2010/09/rosey-chan- Rosey Chan - Vogue.it<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''ONE'' (2010) \n* ''8 YEARS OF MY LIFE'' \n\n===Compositions (Films)===\n* ''Improvisation for the Left Hand''\n* ''China-Town'' 2011 \n* ''An afternoon in Como'' 2014 \n* ''A day in the life''... \n* ''Jaguar Cars campaign 'Alive' ''\n* ''Parametricism | Patrik Schumacher | Zaha Hadid and Rosey Chan'' \n* ''Millennial ''\n* ''Adagio for Planet Earth''\n* ''Besame''\n* ''Petrolo''\n* ''My First Red Dress''\n* ''Suspicious Talks''\n* ''Prague 1850''\n\n\n\n===Documentaries===\n*<nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/> ''One & Other a'' <nowiki/>''Portrait of Trafalgar Square'' - Music [[One & Other]] (Red Mullet, 2009) \n*<nowiki/>''Sky Arts'' ''3D'' - '<nowiki/>''Diva' -'' Music (China-Town Productions, Red Mullet 2009)\n*<nowiki/> <nowiki/>''Just Tell The T''<nowiki/>''ruth, Royal Opera House,'' Deloitte (2011) \n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.roseychan.com Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan, Rosey}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Rosey Chan''' is a multimedia artist. \n\nA virtuoso musician who studied piano and composition at the Royal College of Music, Rosey\u2019s creative output spans a wide range. \n\nHer solo concerts incorporate cinematic visuals and combine her own compositions with selected classical repertoire and electronic fusion. \n\nHer interests in collaborative projects have taken her into a world of contrasted disciplines; Architecture, Design, Poetic Spoken word, Contemporary dance, Experimental music, and Film composition. \n\nRosey is a [[Steinway Artist]].\n\n\n==Background==\n\nRosey Chan was born in the [[United Kingdom]] to Chinese parents. She attended the [[Royal Academy of Music]] on a piano scholarship. She then went on to be classically trained in composition, piano and violin at the [[Royal College of Music]] in [[South Kensington]], London. She also plays guitar, accordion, and keyboards.\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter graduating from the Royal College of Music, Chan performed in a contemporary female duo (two pianos) which performed at such venues as the [[Royal Albert Hall]], [[Wigmore Hall]], [[Royal Festival Hall]] and [[Carnegie Hall]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/jul/15/classicalmusicandopera Yukawa/Chan, Wigmore 