{"title_page": "Alexandrium", "text_new": "{{for|the alga genus|Alexandrium (genus)}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name           = Alexandrium\n| native_name    = \n| alternate_name = Alexandreion, Sartaba\n| image          = Sartaba3.jpg\n| caption        = Wall at Alexandrium\n| alt            = \n| map_type       = Palestinian territories\n| map_alt        = \n| map_size       = \n| relief         = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|32|5|45|N|35|27|41|E|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Jericho Governorate]], [[West Bank]]\n| region         = [[Judea]]\n| type           = Fortification\n| part_of        = \n| length         = \n| width          = \n| area           = \n| height         = \n| builder        = Probably [[Alexander Jannaeus]] \n| material       = \n| built          = 1st century BCE\n| abandoned      = About 70 CE\n| epochs         = [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic]] to [[Roman Empire]]\n| cultures       = \n| dependency_of  = \n| occupants      = \n| event          = \n| excavations    = \n| archaeologists = \n| condition      = \n| ownership      = \n| management     = \n| public_access  = \n| website        = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes          = \n}}\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 31541 Mt. Sartaba.JPG|thumb|Mount Sartaba, once topped by Alexandrium fortress]]\n\n'''Alexandreion'''<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fDMyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT392 | title=Herod: King of the Jews and Friend of the Romans | publisher=Routledge | accessdate=21 June 2018 | author=Peter Richardson, Amy Marie Fisher | year=2018 | edition=2 | page=392 | isbn=978-1-1388-0392-3}}</ref> (Greek), or '''Alexandrium''' (Latin), called '''Sartaba''' in the [[Mishna]] and [[Talmud]] and '''Qarn Sartaba''' in [[Arabic]], was an ancient hilltop fortress constructed by the [[Hasmoneans]]<ref name=ant13417/> between [[Beit She'an|Scythopolis]] and [[Jerusalem]] on a pointy barren hill towering over the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]] from the west.<ref name=rocca/> It was likely named after Hasmonean king [[Alexander Jann\u00e6us]] (104-77 BCE).\n\n==Name==\nThe fortress called \"Alexandreion\" in Greek, simplified to \"Alexandrion\" (and Latinised as \"Alexandrium\"), is mentioned by [[Josephus]] in his ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]''. It was mentioned in the [[Mishna]] and [[Talmud]] as \"Sartaba\" and is now called \"Qarn Sartabe\" (lit. \"Horn of Sartabe\") in [[Arabic]].<ref name=\"Schalit\">[[Abraham Schalit]], ''K\u00f6nig Herodes. Der Mann und sein Werk.'' Walter de Gruyter Inc., Studia Judaica, 2001, p. 12, footnote 40. German: \"Josephus, AJ, XIV, 3, 4 (Par. 49). Alexandreion ist das Sartaba der Mischnah und des Talmud, heute Qarn Sartabe, etwa drei Meilen s\u00fcdwestlich von der M\u00fcndung des Jabboq in den Jordan.\" English translation: \"Josephus, Antiquities of the Jews, XIV, 3, 4 (par. 49). Alexandreion is the Sartaba of the Mishnah and Talmud, today's Qarn Sartabe, about three miles southwest of the confluence of the Jabboq with the Jordan.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ww_0CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=alexandreion+sartaba&source=bl&ots=3oKGEL8BPk&sig=ta_E5mB8N4SDTREdCDYGgFtX3YA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXguK-xurLAhVCGg4KHWnVCgQQ6AEIIDAI#v=onepage&q=alexandreion%20sartaba&f=false]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Khan Sartabeh aqueduct from the 1871-77 Palestine Exploration Fund Survey of Palestine.jpg|thumb|left|Khan Sartabeh aqueduct from the 1871-77 [[PEF Survey of Palestine]]]]\nAlexandrium was constructed by the Hasmoneans near the border with [[Samaria]] to accommodate a military garrison, as well as to guard political prisoners.<ref name=rocca12/> It is later mentioned during [[Pompey the Great]]'s conquest of Judea as a stronghold of [[Aristobulus II]]:  \"...as he passed by [[Pella, Jordan|Pella]] and [[Beit She'an|Scythopolis]], he came to Corem, which is the first entrance into Judea when one passes over the midland countries, where he came to a most beautiful fortress that was built on the top of a mountain called Alexandrium, whither Aristobulus had fled/\"<ref name=ant14/>\n\nThe Alexandreion was restored by [[Herod the Great]], a task he assigned to his brother [[Pheroras]]. Herod gave it the character of a palatial desert fortress, similar to those he built or rebuilt at [[Masada]], [[Herodion]] and [[Machaerus]]. Herod used the fortress as a prison for his political opponents, holding his 2nd wife, [[Mariamne (second wife of Herod)|Mariamne]] and her mother, Alexandra there in 30 BCE. It was also the burial site of [[Alexander, son of Herod]], and [[Aristobulus IV|Aristobulus]], two of his sons whom Herod had executed at [[Sebastia, Nablus|Sebaste]] in 7 BCE.<ref name=rocca/>\n\nAlexandrium was finally razed by [[Vespasian]] or [[Titus]] during the [[First Jewish\u2013Roman War|Great Revolt]].<ref name=enc/>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=rocca>[[#Rocca2008|Rocca 2008]], pp. 30-32</ref>\n<ref name=rocca12>[[#Rocca2008|Rocca 2008]], p. 12</ref>\n<ref name=ant13417>[[#Josephus|Josephus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D13%3Asection%3D416 ''Antiquities of the Jews'' 13:417]</ref> \n<ref name=ant14>[[#Josephus|Josephus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D14%3Asection%3D48''Antiquities of the Jews'' 14:48]</ref> \n<ref name=enc>{{cite web |url= http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=1177&letter=A |title= ALEXANDRIUM |publisher= JewishEncyclopedia.com |last= Krauss |first= Samuel |accessdate= May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*<cite id=Josephus> Josephus, Flavius. William Whiston, A.M., translator (1895). ''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0148 The Works of Flavius Josephus]''. Auburn and Buffalo, New York: John E. Beardsley. Retrieved 15 July 2010.</cite>\n*{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Gup5vH_B-aoC |last=Rocca |first= Samuel |year=2008 |title= The Forts of Judaea 168 BC \u2013 AD 73 |location= Oxford, United Kingdom |publisher= Osprey Publishing |isbn= 978-1-84603-171-7 |ref= Rocca2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sartaba}}\n*[http://holyland-pictures.com/tag/jordan-valley/sartaba/ Pictures of Alexandrium-Sartaba]\n{{Towns depopulated during the First Jewish\u2013Roman War}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:National parks of Israel]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving the Roman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the alga genus|Alexandrium (genus)}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name           = Alexandrium\n| native_name    = \n| alternate_name = Alexandreion, Sartaba\n| image          = Sartaba3.jpg\n| caption        = Wall at Alexandrium\n| alt            = \n| map_type       = Palestinian territories\n| map_alt        = \n| map_size       = \n| relief         = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|32|5|45|N|35|27|41|E|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Jericho Governorate]], [[West Bank]]\n| region         = [[Judea]]\n| type           = Fortification\n| part_of        = \n| length         = \n| width          = \n| area           = \n| height         = \n| builder        = Probably [[Alexander Jannaeus]] \n| material       = \n| built          = 1st century BCE\n| abandoned      = About 70 CE\n| epochs         = [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic]] to [[Roman Empire]]\n| cultures       = \n| dependency_of  = \n| occupants      = \n| event          = \n| excavations    = \n| archaeologists = \n| condition      = \n| ownership      = \n| management     = \n| public_access  = \n| website        = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes          = \n}}\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 31541 Mt. Sartaba.JPG|thumb|Mount Sartaba, once topped by Alexandrium fortress]]\n\n'''Alexandreion'''<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fDMyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT392 | title=Herod: King of the Jews and Friend of the Romans | publisher=Routledge | accessdate=21 June 2018 | author=Peter Richardson, Amy Marie Fisher | year=2018 | edition=2 | page=392 | isbn=978-1-1388-0392-3}}</ref> (Greek), or '''Alexandrium''' (Latin), called '''Sartaba''' in the [[Mishna]] and [[Talmud]] and '''Qarn Sartaba''' in [[Arabic]], was an ancient hilltop fortress constructed by the [[Hasmoneans]]<ref name=ant13417/> between [[Beit She'an|Scythopolis]] and [[Jerusalem]] on a pointy barren hill towering over the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Jordan Valley]] from the west.<ref name=rocca/> It was likely named after Hasmonean king [[Alexander Jann\u00e6us]] (104-77 BCE).\n\n==Name==\nThe fortress called \"Alexandreion\" in Greek, simplified to \"Alexandrion\" (and Latinised as \"Alexandrium\"), is mentioned by [[Josephus]] in his ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]''. It was mentioned in the [[Mishna]] and [[Talmud]] as \"Sartaba\" and is now called \"Qarn Sartabe\" (lit. \"Horn of Sartabe\") in [[Arabic]].<ref name=\"Schalit\">[[Abraham Schalit]], ''K\u00f6nig Herodes. Der Mann und sein Werk.'' Walter de Gruyter Inc., Studia Judaica, 2001, p. 12, footnote 40. German: \"Josephus, AJ, XIV, 3, 4 (Par. 49). Alexandreion ist das Sartaba der Mischnah und des Talmud, heute Qarn Sartabe, etwa drei Meilen s\u00fcdwestlich von der M\u00fcndung des Jabboq in den Jordan.\" English translation: \"Josephus, Antiquities of the Jews, XIV, 3, 4 (par. 49). Alexandreion is the Sartaba of the Mishnah and Talmud, today's Qarn Sartabe, about three miles southwest of the confluence of the Jabboq with the Jordan.\" [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ww_0CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=alexandreion+sartaba&source=bl&ots=3oKGEL8BPk&sig=ta_E5mB8N4SDTREdCDYGgFtX3YA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXguK-xurLAhVCGg4KHWnVCgQQ6AEIIDAI#v=onepage&q=alexandreion%20sartaba&f=false]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Khan Sartabeh aqueduct from the 1871-77 Palestine Exploration Fund Survey of Palestine.jpg|thumb|left|Khan Sartabeh aqueduct from the 1871-77 [[PEF Survey of Palestine]]]]\nAlexandrium was constructed by the Hasmoneans near the border with [[Samaria]] to accommodate a military garrison, as well as to guard political prisoners.<ref name=rocca12/> It is later mentioned during [[Pompey the Great]]'s conquest of Judea as a stronghold of [[Aristobulus II]]:  \"...as he passed by [[Pella, Jordan|Pella]] and [[Beit She'an|Scythopolis]], he came to Corem, which is the first entrance into Judea when one passes over the midland countries, where he came to a most beautiful fortress that was built on the top of a mountain called Alexandrium, whither Aristobulus had fled/\"<ref name=ant14/>\n\nThe Alexandreion was restored by [[Herod the Great]], a task he assigned to his brother [[Pheroras]]. Herod gave it the character of a palatial desert fortress, similar to those he built or rebuilt at [[Masada]], [[Herodion]] and [[Machaerus]]. Herod used the fortress as a prison for his political opponents, holding his 2nd wife, [[Mariamne (second wife of Herod)|Mariamne]] and her mother, Alexandra there in 30 BCE. It was also the burial site of [[Alexander, son of Herod]], and [[Aristobulus IV|Aristobulus]], two of his sons whom Herod had executed at [[Sebastia, Nablus|Sebaste]] in 7 BCE.<ref name=rocca/>\n\nAlexandrium was finally razed by [[Vespasian]] or [[Titus]] during the [[First Jewish\u2013Roman War|Great Revolt]].<ref name=enc/>\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=rocca>[[#Rocca2008|Rocca 2008]], pp. 30-32</ref>\n<ref name=rocca12>[[#Rocca2008|Rocca 2008]], p. 12</ref>\n<ref name=ant13417>[[#Josephus|Josephus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D13%3Asection%3D416 ''Antiquities of the Jews'' 13:417]</ref> \n<ref name=ant14>[[#Josephus|Josephus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D14%3Asection%3D48''Antiquities of the Jews'' 14:48]</ref> \n<ref name=enc>{{cite web |url= http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=1177&letter=A |title= ALEXANDRIUM |publisher= JewishEncyclopedia.com |last= Krauss |first= Samuel |accessdate= May 7, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*<cite id=Josephus> Josephus, Flavius. William Whiston, A.M., translator (1895). ''[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0148 The Works of Flavius Josephus]''. Auburn and Buffalo, New York: John E. Beardsley. Retrieved 15 July 2010.</cite>\n*{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Gup5vH_B-aoC |last=Rocca |first= Samuel |year=2008 |title= The Forts of Judaea 168 BC \u2013 AD 73 |location= Oxford, United Kingdom |publisher= Osprey Publishing |isbn= 978-1-84603-171-7 |ref= Rocca2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sartaba}}\n*[http://holyland-pictures.com/tag/jordan-valley/sartaba/ Pictures of Alexandrium-Sartaba]\n{{Towns depopulated during the First Jewish\u2013Roman War}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:National parks of Israel]]\n[[Category:Sieges involving the Roman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandrium"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Morrison National Park", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                   = protected\n| name                   = Alexander Morrison National Park\n| state                  = wa\n| iucn_category          = II\n| image                  = \n| caption                = \n| image_alt              = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|30|05|02|S|115|29|10|E|display=inline,title}}\n| relief                 = yes\n| map_alt                = \n| nearest_town_or_city   = [[Coorow, Western Australia|Coorow]]\n| area                   = 85\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=\"ParkAreas\">{{cite journal|year=2010 |title=Department of Environment and Conservation 2009\u20132010 Annual Report |pages=48 |publisher=Department of Environment and Conservation |issn=1835-114X |url=http://www.dec.wa.gov.au/content/view/6139/2345/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111124319/http://www.dec.wa.gov.au/content/view/6139/2345/ |archivedate=11 January 2011 }}</ref>\n| established            = 1970\n| established_footnotes  = \n| visitation_num         = \n| visitation_year        = \n| visitation_footnotes   = \n| managing_authorities   = [[Parks and Wildlife Service (Western Australia)|Parks and Wildlife Service]]\n| url                    = https://parks.dpaw.wa.gov.au/park/alexander-morrison\n}}\n'''Alexander Morrison National Park''' is a national park in [[Western Australia]], located {{convert|207|km|mi|0}} north of [[Perth]] in the [[Shire of Coorow]] along the Green Head-Coorow Road. It was named for [[Alexander Morrison (botanist)|Alexander Morrison]], the first Government Botanist of Western Australia.\n\n==Description==\nThe {{convert|8500|ha|acre|0}} park contains sandplains and low [[laterite|lateritic]] breakaways over [[sandstone]]s and [[shale]]s of the [[Early Jurassic|Lower Jurassic]] Cockleshell Gully Formation. Sand [[heath (habitat)|heath]]s are the dominant vegetation, but the park also contains extensive stands of low woodland and mallee typical of the area,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/Western-Australia/Eneabba/2005/02/17/1108500208425.html|title=Travel - Eneabba|date=8 February 2004|author=Fairfax Digital|accessdate=11 August 2007| work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> especially in the western parts of the park. Prominent eucalypt species in the area are Powder-barked Wandoo (''[[Eucalyptus accedens]]'') and Mallalie (''[[Eucalyptus eudesmoides|E. eudesmoides]]''), while the heaths are rich in species typical of the region and include rare species such as spiral bush (''[[Spirogardnera rubescens]]''). The northern variant of ''[[Banksia vestita]]'' is also common.<ref name=ctrc74>{{cite book|title=Conservation Reserves in Western Australia - Report 1974 (Green Book)|author=Conservation through Reserves Committee|publisher=[[Environmental Protection Authority of Western Australia]]|date=31 January 1975|isbn=0-7244-5934-0 | pages = 5\u201321}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLand for the national park was set aside by the Department of Lands and Surveys under Reserves \u219126800, \u219126803 and \u219126804 on 23 May 1969, and over 1970 and 1971, the land was classified as an \"A\" Class reserve, meaning its purpose could not be changed except by an Act of Parliament,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=C. F. H. (Clee)|year=1980|title=The National Parks of Western Australia|publisher=National Parks Authority of Western Australia|isbn=0-7244-8176-1|page=19}}</ref> and vested in the National Parks Authority of Western Australia. The park was officially named on 8 October 1971.<ref>{{Gazette WA | title = Reserves | page=1969:1529 | file = 1183/69, 1184/69, 1185/69 | date = 23 May 1969}} (Reserves 26800, 26803 and 26804)<br />* {{Gazette WA | title = Land Act 1933-1969 - Order in Council | page = 1970:2029 | file = 1183/69 | date = 10 July 1970}} See also 29 January 1971 p. 1971:278, 19 February 1971 p. 1971:452.<br />* {{Gazette WA | title = Naming of Alexander Morrison National Park | page = 1971:3952 | file = 2531/54 V2 | date = 8 October 1971}}</ref>\n\nThe Environmental Protection Authority recommended in 1974 that a one-kilometre-wide strip of vacant Crown land on the south side of Green Head-Coorow Road be added to the reserve<ref name=ctrc74/> \u2013 however, this was not actioned.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Protected areas of Western Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Parks of Western Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Mid West (Western Australia)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                   = protected\n| name                   = Alexander Morrison National Park\n| state                  = wa\n| iucn_category          = II\n| image                  = \n| caption                = \n| image_alt              = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|30|05|02|S|115|29|10|E|display=inline,title}}\n| relief                 = yes\n| map_alt                = \n| nearest_town_or_city   = [[Coorow, Western Australia|Coorow]]\n| area                   = 85\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=\"ParkAreas\">{{cite journal|year=2010 |title=Department of Environment and Conservation 2009\u20132010 Annual Report |pages=48 |publisher=Department of Environment and Conservation |issn=1835-114X |url=http://www.dec.wa.gov.au/content/view/6139/2345/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111124319/http://www.dec.wa.gov.au/content/view/6139/2345/ |archivedate=11 January 2011 }}</ref>\n| established            = 1970\n| established_footnotes  = \n| visitation_num         = \n| visitation_year        = \n| visitation_footnotes   = \n| managing_authorities   = [[Parks and Wildlife Service (Western Australia)|Parks and Wildlife Service]]\n| url                    = https://parks.dpaw.wa.gov.au/park/alexander-morrison\n}}\n'''Alexander Morrison National Park''' is a national park in [[Western Australia]], located {{convert|207|km|mi|0}} north of [[Perth]] in the [[Shire of Coorow]] along the Green Head-Coorow Road. It was named for [[Alexander Morrison (botanist)|Alexander Morrison]], the first Government Botanist of Western Australia.\n\n==Description==\nThe {{convert|8500|ha|acre|0}} park contains sandplains and low [[laterite|lateritic]] breakaways over [[sandstone]]s and [[shale]]s of the [[Early Jurassic|Lower Jurassic]] Cockleshell Gully Formation. Sand [[heath (habitat)|heath]]s are the dominant vegetation, but the park also contains extensive stands of low woodland and mallee typical of the area,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/Western-Australia/Eneabba/2005/02/17/1108500208425.html|title=Travel - Eneabba|date=8 February 2004|author=Fairfax Digital|accessdate=11 August 2007| work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> especially in the western parts of the park. Prominent eucalypt species in the area are Powder-barked Wandoo (''[[Eucalyptus accedens]]'') and Mallalie (''[[Eucalyptus eudesmoides|E. eudesmoides]]''), while the heaths are rich in species typical of the region and include rare species such as spiral bush (''[[Spirogardnera rubescens]]''). The northern variant of ''[[Banksia vestita]]'' is also common.<ref name=ctrc74>{{cite book|title=Conservation Reserves in Western Australia - Report 1974 (Green Book)|author=Conservation through Reserves Committee|publisher=[[Environmental Protection Authority of Western Australia]]|date=31 January 1975|isbn=0-7244-5934-0 | pages = 5\u201321}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLand for the national park was set aside by the Department of Lands and Surveys under Reserves \u219126800, \u219126803 and \u219126804 on 23 May 1969, and over 1970 and 1971, the land was classified as an \"A\" Class reserve, meaning its purpose could not be changed except by an Act of Parliament,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=C. F. H. (Clee)|year=1980|title=The National Parks of Western Australia|publisher=National Parks Authority of Western Australia|isbn=0-7244-8176-1|page=19}}</ref> and vested in the National Parks Authority of Western Australia. The park was officially named on 8 October 1971.<ref>{{Gazette WA | title = Reserves | page=1969:1529 | file = 1183/69, 1184/69, 1185/69 | date = 23 May 1969}} (Reserves 26800, 26803 and 26804)<br />* {{Gazette WA | title = Land Act 1933-1969 - Order in Council | page = 1970:2029 | file = 1183/69 | date = 10 July 1970}} See also 29 January 1971 p. 1971:278, 19 February 1971 p. 1971:452.<br />* {{Gazette WA | title = Naming of Alexander Morrison National Park | page = 1971:3952 | file = 2531/54 V2 | date = 8 October 1971}}</ref>\n\nThe Environmental Protection Authority recommended in 1974 that a one-kilometre-wide strip of vacant Crown land on the south side of Green Head-Coorow Road be added to the reserve<ref name=ctrc74/> \u2013 however, this was not actioned.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Protected areas of Western Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Parks of Western Australia}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Mid West (Western Australia)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Morrison_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "Alerce Costero National Park", "text_new": "{{Infobox Protected area\n| name = Alerce Costero National Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| photo = Cordillera Pelada.jpg\n| photo_caption =\n| location = [[La Uni\u00f3n, Chile]] [[Communes of Chile|commune]], [[Los R\u00edos Region]], [[Chile]]\n| nearest_city = [[La Uni\u00f3n, Chile]]\n| map = Chile\n| relief = 1\n| coordinates = {{coords|40|11|0|S|73|28|0|W|display=inline, title}}\n| area_ha = 24,000\n| established = 1987, changed status in 2012 to National Reserve<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conaf.cl/parques/ficha-monumento_natural_alerce_costero-29.html|title=Alerce costero National Park|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328101247/http://www.conaf.cl/parques/ficha-monumento_natural_alerce_costero-29.html |archivedate=2013-03-28|publisher=CONAF Chile|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n| visitation_num =\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[Corporaci\u00f3n Nacional Forestal]]\n}}\n[[File:Guigna 2.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Kodkod]].]]\n[[File:Magellanic Woodpecker Male (Campephilus magellanicus).jpg|thumb|200px|Black or Magellanic woodpecker]]\n'''Alerce Costero National Park''' ({{lang-es|Parque Nacional Alerce Costero}}, {{IPA-es|a\u02c8le\u027ese  kos\u02c8te\u027eo|am}}) is a protected wild area in the [[Cordillera Pelada]] about {{convert|137|km|mi|abbr=in}} from [[Valdivia, Chile|Valdivia]] and {{convert|49|km|mi|abbr=in}} from [[La Uni\u00f3n, Chile|La Uni\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisischile.cl/7485/2/chile-debuts-national-park-to-protect-ancient-alerce-forests/News.aspx|title=Chile debuts national park to protect ancient alerce forests|publisher=thisischile.cl|date=2014-02-07|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref> ''[[Fitzroya]]'' trees grow inside the protected area and give the area its name, with ''Alerce Costero'' translating as ''Coastal Fitzroya''. The Natural Monument has a total area of {{convert|137|ha|acre|abbr=off|lk=in}}.\n\n==History==\nAlerce Costero National Park has its origins in the [[natural monument|National Monument]] Alerce Costero, created on January 3, 1987, by the [[Ministries of Chile|Chilean government]].\nIn 2012 the area was elevated to national park status and was renamed '''Alerce Costero National Park''' (Spanish: Parque Nacional Alerce Costero).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/tendencias/ciencia-tecnologia/2012/02/739-428711-9-crean-nuevo-parque-nacional-alerce-costero.shtml|title=Crean nuevo Parque Nacional Alerce Costero|newspaper=[[La Tercera]]|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=2012-02-03|language=es}}</ref>\nThe new national park is the result of a public-private collaboration that united the state-owned  Alerce Costero National Monument, Valdivia National Reserve and Quitaluto estate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gob.cl/destacados/2012/02/03/presidente-pinera-encabezo-traspaso-al-estado-de-9-500-hectareas-para-la-creacion-del-parque-naciona.htm|title=Presidente Pi\u00f1era encabez\u00f3 traspaso al Estado de 9.500 hect\u00e1reas para la creaci\u00f3n del Parque Nacional Alerce Costero en la regi\u00f3n de Los R\u00edos|date=2013-02-03|accessdate=2014-02-10|language=es}}</ref> with land donated by [[The Nature Conservancy]], which also owns the adjacent [[Valdivian Coastal Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reservacosteravaldiviana.cl/|title=Reserva Costera Valdiviana official web site|accessdate=2014-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930132632/http://www.reservacosteravaldiviana.cl/|archive-date=2016-09-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\nThe park is administered by [[National Forest Corporation (Chile)|CONAF]]  (the Chilean National Forest Corporation), has a total surface area of {{convert|137|ha|acre|abbr=off}}, and rises to a maximum [[altitude]] of {{convert|1048|m|ft|abbr=in}}. The geography of the park make it suitable for many species of endemic birds and mammals with very specific habitat requirement.\nOne of the goals of the park is to protect the [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]] and help maintain Chaihu\u00edn river basin, an important watercourse in the region, while also protecting the [[Chaihu\u00edn]] community that depend on the river.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parques-selvavaldiviana.cl/index.php/parques/destino-valdivia-corral/parque-nacional-alerce-costero|title=Parque Nacional Alerce Costero|publisher=parques-selvavaldiviana.cl|accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref>\nThe unique ecosystem of the southern [[Chilean Coast Range]] and [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]] makes this a priority site for biodiversity conservation. The mountainous area served as a refuge from the devastating effects of the [[Last glacial period|last glaciation]] which occurred during the [[Quaternary]] Period, and more recently from the effects of volcanic activity. It has not, however, been kept safe human activity and is today classes as a threatened area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chile.panda.org/que_hacemos/protegiendo_biodiversidad/areas_protegidas/parque_alerce_costero/|title=Parque Alerce Costero|publisher=WWF Chile|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n\nFrom about 1750 to 1943, when the land between [[Maull\u00edn River]] and [[Valdivia]] was colonized by Spain and then Chile, numerous fires of ''Fitzroya'' woods occurred in [[Cordillera Pelada]]. These fires were initiated by Spaniards, Chileans and Europeans. Earlier, from 1397 to 1750 the ''Fitzroya'' woods of Cordillera Pelada also suffered from fires that originated from lightning strikes and indigenous inhabitants.<ref>{{Citation\n |last1       = Lara\n |first1      = A.\n |last2       = Fraver\n |first2      = S.\n |last3       = Aravena\n |first3      = J.C.\n |last4       = Wolodarsky-Franke\n |first4      = F.\n |title       = Fire and the dynamics of Fitzroya cupressoides (alerce) forests of Chile's Cordillera Pelada\n |journal     = [[\u00c9coscience]]\n |volume      = 6\n |issue       = 1\n |year        = 1999\n |pages       = 100\u2013109\n |url         = http://www.ecoscience.ulaval.ca/en/paper/fire-and-the-dynamics-of-fitzroya-cupressoides-alerce-forests-of-chile-s-cordillera-pelada\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140827141331/http://www.ecoscience.ulaval.ca/en/paper/fire-and-the-dynamics-of-fitzroya-cupressoides-alerce-forests-of-chile-s-cordillera-pelada\n |archivedate = 2014-08-27\n}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nThe area of [[Valdivia]] and the [[Los R\u00edos Region]] has a rainy temperate climate, with rains all year round. The park is slightly warmer than the rest of the region, with an average annual temperature of 12\u00b0 [[Celsius]] and temperatures ranging from being {{convert|17.2|C|F|0}} in January and the {{convert|7.6|C|F}} in July.\n\n==Location and access==\n[[File:Alercecosterovista.JPG|thumb|250px|right|upright|''[[Fitzroya]]'' forest at Alerce Costero National Park, Chile.]]\nThe park is part of the [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]], and located in the [[Chilean Coast Range|Coastal Range]] of the [[Comunnes of Chile|communes]] of [[Corral, Chile|Corral]] and [[La Uni\u00f3n, Chile|La Uni\u00f3n]]. There are works in progress to improve access to the park but the use of four wheel drive vehicles is currently recommended.\n \n; Access from Corral\nThe main access is route T-80 that runs from [[Corral, Chile|Corral]] to the seaside village of Hueicolla. The road consists of {{convert|31|km|mi|abbr=in}} of gravel and {{convert|17|km|mi|abbr=in}} of dirt road, suitable only for off-road vehicles or mountain bikes. There is an alternative route for standard vehicles via the road joining La Uni\u00f3n and Santa Elisa in the Cumleufu area.\nOther ways of accessing the park from Corral (all suitable for four wheel drives and mountain bikes only) include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surturistico.cl/index.php/turismo-region-de-los-rios/319-parque-nacional-alerce-costero-|title=Parque Nacional Alerce Costero, Regi\u00f3n de Los R\u00edos|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301030114/http://www.surturistico.cl/index.php/turismo-region-de-los-rios/319-parque-nacional-alerce-costero- |archivedate=2014-03-01|publisher=surturistico.cl|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n* 1C Access: West entrance, approaching from the town of Chaihu\u00edn in Corral commune, towards the Catrileufu zone that used to be part of the former Valdivia National Reserve.\n* 2C Access: North entrance from Corral, following route T- 470, to the Quitaluto-Catrilelfu zone. \n* 3C Access: North entrance from the town of Morro Gonzalo Corral in the commune of the Quitaluto. \n* 4C Access: Entrance from route T-60 via the Valdivia \u2013 La Union Highway (Route T -640) in the Tres Chiflones zone, toward La Romaza by a dirt road.\n \n; Accesses from La Uni\u00f3n\n* 1U access: South entrance from the town of Santa Elisa in the commune of La Uni\u00f3n to the La Romaza area,. The road is in good condition and suitable for all vehicles.\n* 2U Access: Entrance via route T-80 from La Uni\u00f3n to the Alto Mirador area. The gravel road is in good condition and is suitable for all vehicles.\n\nThere is also a river access from the Chaihu\u00edn river and a {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=off|adj=on}} four wheel drive route that runs from the coast via route T-470 to Hueicolla, and from there to route T-80.\n\n===Main features and activities===\n\nEntry to the park is free, and it is open daily from 9:00 to 20:00.\nAs its name suggests, one of the main features of the park are the ancient [[Fitzroya]] trees, some of which are thousands of years old, especially in the southern area of the park.\nThe evergreen forest has burnt out patches where forest fires have left their mark, which have given the area its alternative name: \"Cordillera Pelada\" or \"Bald Mountains.\"\n\nThe park is suitable for [[hiking]] and [[horseback riding]], and has several viewpoints and places to observe the flora, fauna and landscapes. The park is a particularly popular site for mountain biking.\nIn the north area (Catrilelfu, Las Romazas) there is a [[National Forest Corporation (Chile)|CONAF]] office with park rangers, tourist information and safety advice. Toilets and trash cans are located around the park.\nThe park has two short official trail routes, both located in the southern part, although more than {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=in}} of further trails are being explored and equipped for visitors.\n* The 1,800 \"Alerce Milenario\" (Ancient Fitzroya) route leads to a 3,000-year-old, {{convert|4.5|m|ft|adj=mid|-wide}} Fitzroya tree.\n* The \"Piedra del Indio\" (Indian Stone) route leads to an area with views of the mountain range and river. Here can be found examples of \u201cCipr\u00e9s de las Guaitecas\u201d or ([[Pilgerodendron]]).\nThere is a camping zone with some equipment such as tables, a wooden shelter, and information.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nAmong the many species that can be found in the Alerce Costero National Park are:\n;Flora\n* Alerce (''[[Fitzroya]]'')\n* Canelo (''[[Drimys winteri]]'')\n* Cipr\u00e9s de las Guaitecas (''[[Pilgerodendron]]'')\n* Tineo (''[[Weinmannia trichosperma]]'')\n* Coig\u00fce de Chilo\u00e9 (''[[Nothofagus nitida]]'')\n* Two kinds of carnivorous plants: \u201crocio del sol\u201d (''[[Drosera uniflora]]'') and \u201cvioleta del pantano\u201d (''[[Pinguicula chilensis]]'')\n;Fauna\n* G\u00fci\u00f1a ([[kodkod]])\n* Puma ([[cougar|''Felis concolor'' or cougar]])\n* Quique ([[lesser grison]])\n* [[Pud\u00fa]] \n* Carpintero negro ([[Magellanic woodpecker]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of national parks of Chile]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n{{National Parks of Chile}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alerce costero national park}}\n[[Category:Protected areas of Los R\u00edos Region]]\n[[Category:National parks of Chile]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1988]]\n[[Category:2012 in Chilean law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Protected area\n| name = Alerce Costero National Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| phot