In 2012 the area was elevated to national park status and was renamed '''Alerce Costero National Park''' (Spanish: Parque Nacional Alerce Costero).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/tendencias/ciencia-tecnologia/2012/02/739-428711-9-crean-nuevo-parque-nacional-alerce-costero.shtml|title=Crean nuevo Parque Nacional Alerce Costero|newspaper=[[La Tercera]]|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=2012-02-03|language=es}}</ref>\nThe new national park is the result of a public-private collaboration that united the state-owned  Alerce Costero National Monument, Valdivia National Reserve and Quitaluto estate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gob.cl/destacados/2012/02/03/presidente-pinera-encabezo-traspaso-al-estado-de-9-500-hectareas-para-la-creacion-del-parque-naciona.htm|title=Presidente Pi\u00f1era encabez\u00f3 traspaso al Estado de 9.500 hect\u00e1reas para la creaci\u00f3n del Parque Nacional Alerce Costero en la regi\u00f3n de Los R\u00edos|date=2013-02-03|accessdate=2014-02-10|language=es}}</ref> with land donated by [[The Nature Conservancy]], which also owns the adjacent [[Valdivian Coastal Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reservacosteravaldiviana.cl/|title=Reserva Costera Valdiviana official web site|accessdate=2014-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930132632/http://www.reservacosteravaldiviana.cl/|archive-date=2016-09-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\nThe park is administered by [[National Forest Corporation (Chile)|CONAF]]  (the Chilean National Forest Corporation), has a total surface area of {{convert|137|ha|acre|abbr=off}}, and rises to a maximum [[altitude]] of {{convert|1048|m|ft|abbr=in}}. The geography of the park make it suitable for many species of endemic birds and mammals with very specific habitat requirement.\nOne of the goals of the park is to protect the [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]] and help maintain Chaihu\u00edn river basin, an important watercourse in the region, while also protecting the [[Chaihu\u00edn]] community that depend on the river.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parques-selvavaldiviana.cl/index.php/parques/destino-valdivia-corral/parque-nacional-alerce-costero|title=Parque Nacional Alerce Costero|publisher=parques-selvavaldiviana.cl|accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref>\nThe unique ecosystem of the southern [[Chilean Coast Range]] and [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]] makes this a priority site for biodiversity conservation. The mountainous area served as a refuge from the devastating effects of the [[Last glacial period|last glaciation]] which occurred during the [[Quaternary]] Period, and more recently from the effects of volcanic activity. It has not, however, been kept safe human activity and is today classes as a threatened area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chile.panda.org/que_hacemos/protegiendo_biodiversidad/areas_protegidas/parque_alerce_costero/|title=Parque Alerce Costero|publisher=WWF Chile|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n\nFrom about 1750 to 1943, when the land between [[Maull\u00edn River]] and [[Valdivia]] was colonized by Spain and then Chile, numerous fires of ''Fitzroya'' woods occurred in [[Cordillera Pelada]]. These fires were initiated by Spaniards, Chileans and Europeans. Earlier, from 1397 to 1750 the ''Fitzroya'' woods of Cordillera Pelada also suffered from fires that originated from lightning strikes and indigenous inhabitants.<ref>{{Citation\n |last1       = Lara\n |first1      = A.\n |last2       = Fraver\n |first2      = S.\n |last3       = Aravena\n |first3      = J.C.\n |last4       = Wolodarsky-Franke\n |first4      = F.\n |title       = Fire and the dynamics of Fitzroya cupressoides (alerce) forests of Chile's Cordillera Pelada\n |journal     = [[\u00c9coscience]]\n |volume      = 6\n |issue       = 1\n |year        = 1999\n |pages       = 100\u2013109\n |url         = http://www.ecoscience.ulaval.ca/en/paper/fire-and-the-dynamics-of-fitzroya-cupressoides-alerce-forests-of-chile-s-cordillera-pelada\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140827141331/http://www.ecoscience.ulaval.ca/en/paper/fire-and-the-dynamics-of-fitzroya-cupressoides-alerce-forests-of-chile-s-cordillera-pelada\n |archivedate = 2014-08-27\n}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n\nThe area of [[Valdivia]] and the [[Los R\u00edos Region]] has a rainy temperate climate, with rains all year round. The park is slightly warmer than the rest of the region, with an average annual temperature of 12\u00b0 [[Celsius]] and temperatures ranging from being {{convert|17.2|C|F|0}} in January and the {{convert|7.6|C|F}} in July.\n\n==Location and access==\n[[File:Alercecosterovista.JPG|thumb|250px|right|upright|''[[Fitzroya]]'' forest at Alerce Costero National Park, Chile.]]\nThe park is part of the [[Valdivian temperate rain forest]], and located in the [[Chilean Coast Range|Coastal Range]] of the [[Comunnes of Chile|communes]] of [[Corral, Chile|Corral]] and [[La Uni\u00f3n, Chile|La Uni\u00f3n]]. There are works in progress to improve access to the park but the use of four wheel drive vehicles is currently recommended.\n \n; Access from Corral\nThe main access is route T-80 that runs from [[Corral, Chile|Corral]] to the seaside village of Hueicolla. The road consists of {{convert|31|km|mi|abbr=in}} of gravel and {{convert|17|km|mi|abbr=in}} of dirt road, suitable only for off-road vehicles or mountain bikes. There is an alternative route for standard vehicles via the road joining La Uni\u00f3n and Santa Elisa in the Cumleufu area.\nOther ways of accessing the park from Corral (all suitable for four wheel drives and mountain bikes only) include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surturistico.cl/index.php/turismo-region-de-los-rios/319-parque-nacional-alerce-costero-|title=Parque Nacional Alerce Costero, Regi\u00f3n de Los R\u00edos|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301030114/http://www.surturistico.cl/index.php/turismo-region-de-los-rios/319-parque-nacional-alerce-costero- |archivedate=2014-03-01|publisher=surturistico.cl|accessdate=2014-02-11}}</ref>\n* 1C Access: West entrance, approaching from the town of Chaihu\u00edn in Corral commune, towards the Catrileufu zone that used to be part of the former Valdivia National Reserve.\n* 2C Access: North entrance from Corral, following route T- 470, to the Quitaluto-Catrilelfu zone. \n* 3C Access: North entrance from the town of Morro Gonzalo Corral in the commune of the Quitaluto. \n* 4C Access: Entrance from route T-60 via the Valdivia \u2013 La Union Highway (Route T -640) in the Tres Chiflones zone, toward La Romaza by a dirt road.\n \n; Accesses from La Uni\u00f3n\n* 1U access: South entrance from the town of Santa Elisa in the commune of La Uni\u00f3n to the La Romaza area,. The road is in good condition and suitable for all vehicles.\n* 2U Access: Entrance via route T-80 from La Uni\u00f3n to the Alto Mirador area. The gravel road is in good condition and is suitable for all vehicles.\n\nThere is also a river access from the Chaihu\u00edn river and a {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=off|adj=on}} four wheel drive route that runs from the coast via route T-470 to Hueicolla, and from there to route T-80.\n\n===Main features and activities===\n\nEntry to the park is free, and it is open daily from 9:00 to 20:00.\nAs its name suggests, one of the main features of the park are the ancient [[Fitzroya]] trees, some of which are thousands of years old, especially in the southern area of the park.\nThe evergreen forest has burnt out patches where forest fires have left their mark, which have given the area its alternative name: \"Cordillera Pelada\" or \"Bald Mountains.\"\n\nThe park is suitable for [[hiking]] and [[horseback riding]], and has several viewpoints and places to observe the flora, fauna and landscapes. The park is a particularly popular site for mountain biking.\nIn the north area (Catrilelfu, Las Romazas) there is a [[National Forest Corporation (Chile)|CONAF]] office with park rangers, tourist information and safety advice. Toilets and trash cans are located around the park.\nThe park has two short official trail routes, both located in the southern part, although more than {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=in}} of further trails are being explored and equipped for visitors.\n* The 1,800 \"Alerce Milenario\" (Ancient Fitzroya) route leads to a 3,000-year-old, {{convert|4.5|m|ft|adj=mid|-wide}} Fitzroya tree.\n* The \"Piedra del Indio\" (Indian Stone) route leads to an area with views of the mountain range and river. Here can be found examples of \u201cCipr\u00e9s de las Guaitecas\u201d or ([[Pilgerodendron]]).\nThere is a camping zone with some equipment such as tables, a wooden shelter, and information.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nAmong the many species that can be found in the Alerce Costero National Park are:\n;Flora\n* Alerce (''[[Fitzroya]]'')\n* Canelo (''[[Drimys winteri]]'')\n* Cipr\u00e9s de las Guaitecas (''[[Pilgerodendron]]'')\n* Tineo (''[[Weinmannia trichosperma]]'')\n* Coig\u00fce de Chilo\u00e9 (''[[Nothofagus nitida]]'')\n* Two kinds of carnivorous plants: \u201crocio del sol\u201d (''[[Drosera uniflora]]'') and \u201cvioleta del pantano\u201d (''[[Pinguicula chilensis]]'')\n;Fauna\n* G\u00fci\u00f1a ([[kodkod]])\n* Puma ([[cougar|''Felis concolor'' or cougar]])\n* Quique ([[lesser grison]])\n* [[Pud\u00fa]] \n* Carpintero negro ([[Magellanic woodpecker]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of national parks of Chile]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n{{National Parks of Chile}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alerce costero national park}}\n[[Category:Protected areas of Los R\u00edos Region]]\n[[Category:National parks of Chile]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1988]]\n[[Category:2012 in Chilean law]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alerce_Costero_National_Park"}
